          <h2 style="font-size:20px;line-height:1.2;font-weight:500; margin-top:16px !important">Belgium crimes</h2>
        </mj-text>
         <mj-image padding="10px 12px" width="600px" src="https://www.geopolitics.world/email/images/gp-dec-5-1.jpg" alt="Belgium crimes" href="https://www.geopolitics.world" />
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.4;">In a landmark decision, Belgium‚Äôs appeals court <a href="https://www.france24.com/en/europe/20241202-belgian-court-rules-against-state-over-abduction-of-mixed-race-children-in-colonial-era-congo" target="_blank">ruled</a> against the state that five mixed-race women, abducted as children from Belgian-ruled Congo and placed in Catholic institutions, were victims of systematic persecution constituting a crime against humanity. The women, now in their 70s, were forcibly separated from their mothers due to their mixed-race origins. The court found this inhumane and immune to statutes of limitation under post-WWII UN resolutions. </p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.4;">The Belgian state was ordered to pay reparations for the moral damage, recognizing the harm caused to their identity and familial ties. The women also demanded compensation of 50,000 euros ($55,200) each. While Belgium formally apologized to the mixed-race descendants of its white colonists in 2019, it is yet to issue an official <a href="https://www.politico.eu/article/belgium-still-struggling-with-its-colonial-ghosts/" target="_blank">apology</a> for slavery and the atrocities committed by King Leopold II.‚Äã</p>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-divider border-width="1px" border-style="solid" border-color="lightgrey" padding="10px 12px" />
      </mj-column>
    </mj-section>
