          <h2 style="font-size:20px;line-height:1.2;font-weight:500;">Martial moves</h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.4;">South Korean President Yoon Suk Yeol declared <a href="https://www.bbc.com/news/articles/c0lgw1pw5zpo" target="_blank">martial law</a> and canceled the decree six hours after the National Assembly rejected it. He claimed it was necessary to combat ‚Äúpro-North Korea forces‚Äù in the opposition but offered no evidence. Kim Sang-woo, a former politician, claims that the opposition party, which won the mid-term election and holds a majority, has been abusing its legislative position to force through bills that Yoon believes are against the national interest. This might have prompted Yoon Suk Yeol to declare martial law.</p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.4;">It was a politically testing year for the president. Yoon highlighted there were 22 impeachments against government officials since he assumed office in 2022 and added that the opposition was weaponizing impeachment. He also saw his approval ratings drop to 19% earlier this week. His party was also angered when the defense budget was cut by 45.7 million euros. South Korea is going to face a period of instability as the standoff between legislature and executive continues.</p>
        </mj-text>
