          <h2 style="font-size:20px;line-height:1.2;font-weight:500; margin-top:16px !important">Why are the Baltics supportive of Ukraine and Georgia?</h2>
        </mj-text>
         <mj-image padding="10px 12px" width="600px" src="https://www.geopolitics.world/email/images/gp-dec-5-3.jpg" alt="Why are the Baltics supportive of Ukraine and Georgia? " href="https://www.geopolitics.world" />
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.4;">When Russia invaded Ukraine in February of 2022, the Baltic states (Estonia, Latvia, Lithuania) were the first to jump to their <a href="https://www.lrt.lt/en/news-in-english/19/1689163/baltics-were-the-first-to-support-ukraine-with-arms-diplomacy-zelensky" target="_blank">support</a>. They have recently come to advocate for the demonstrators in Georgia and sanctioned Georgian ruling officials. Here are a couple of reasons to explain this overwhelming support.</p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.4;">The first one is based on historical memory and shared trauma. The Baltics have a <a href="https://www.britannica.com/place/Baltic-states/Soviet-occupation" target="_blank">history</a> of Soviet occupation, which creates a strong sense of solidarity with countries like Ukraine and Georgia that have been at odds with Russia and its control of these countries. Many of them have traumatic memories of some of the brutality of the Soviet regime; they understand the threat posed by Russia and are determined to support other nations fighting for their sovereignty and independence.‚Äã</p>
           <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.4;">The other reasons are based on geopolitical strategy and security. The Baltics are situated on the eastern edge of NATO and the EU, making them highly vulnerable to Russian expansionism. The annexation of Crimea in 2014 and Russia‚Äôs military actions in Ukraine and Georgia have heightened these security concerns. The conflicts in Georgia and Ukraine make these three members feel uneasy. Although they are NATO members, Russia is less likely to cause conflict with a club member than those in line to try to get into the club.‚Äã</p>
        </mj-text>
      </mj-column>
